## Stage 1: Core Concepts (Week 1)

| Concept | What it is |
|---|---|
| **Controller (master)** | The main Jenkins server — schedules jobs, serves the UI |
| **Agent (node)** | A machine that actually executes the build steps (can be the controller itself or separate workers) |
| **Job / Project** | A single automated task (e.g., "build my-app") |
| **Pipeline** | A job defined as code (`Jenkinsfile`) describing stages: build, test, deploy |
| **Stage** | A logical phase within a pipeline (e.g., "Build", "Test", "Deploy") |
| **Executor** | A slot on an agent that runs one build at a time |
| **Plugin** | Jenkins' extensibility mechanism — Docker, Kubernetes, Git, Slack integrations are all plugins |
| **Workspace** | The directory on the agent where your code is checked out and the build runs |

### Install Jenkins to practice on
Easiest path: run it in Docker (fittingly).
```bash
docker run -d --name jenkins \
  -p 8080:8080 -p 50000:50000 \
  -v jenkins_home:/var/jenkins_home \
  jenkins/jenkins:lts
```
Then visit `http://localhost:8080`, unlock using the initial admin password:
```bash
docker exec jenkins cat /var/jenkins_home/secrets/initialAdminPassword
```
Install suggested plugins, create your first admin user.

**Note:** to let Jenkins build Docker images from inside its own container, you typically
mount the host's Docker socket: add `-v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock` (has
security implications worth understanding, covered in Stage 7).

